  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Safe Drinking Water, Sanitation and Hygiene Support for flood affected communities in Pakistan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">(1) Rehabiliation of water points (2) Construction of new boreholes (3) Hygiene promotion campaigns and sanitation marketing culminating in construction of latrines and capacity building of community volunteers</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Flood affected communities in Dadu, Sindh</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">To prevent malnutrition in children and reduce water related diseases in flood affected communities through improved access to safe water, sanitation, and hygiene. WASH interventions are based on a comprehensive approach to disease reduction that concentrates on preventative interventions. Specifically, WASH interventions will focus on increasing access to sufficient quantities of safe water, increasing access to sanitation facilities, and increasing safe health and hygiene knowledge, particularly among vulnerable populations. These interventions will increase local capacity to manage and trouble shoot water supply, sanitation and poor hygiene through facilitation, including training and accompaniment, of Union Council-level Water Management Committees (WMCs), Basic Health Units (BHUs), and the Union Councils themselves, to ensure the sustainability of programming.</narrative>
  </description>
